\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720 Very good examples. One question, in what (wrong order) did you get (3+5)*8=29?  \par

\pard\nowidctlpar             I 'm glad that you discussed addition/subtraction and multiplication/division.  Actually what you said is true for any expression. In other words, if two operators are next to each other (no other operators or parentheses between them), and they are plus/minus  (or multiply/divide), you should always process the left operator first. \par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\par

\pard\nowidctlpar\b0 Ah, I see. Very creative thinking although such kind of mistake is a bit unusual in real life. Theoretically there is nothing wrong with such order as long as everyone accepts it. Order of operations is just a rule. What matters most is to make sure people stick to the same rule, exact which rule to use often matters little. For example, in most states we drive on the right side of the road, while in US-virgin islands, people drive on the left side of the road. It took me a few minutes to adjust when I traveled there in 2011, but then everything was fine.  Now imagine in the place some people drive on the right-side while others drive on the left-side. Chaos and accidents are bound to happen.\par
\b\par

