\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-720\li720\par

\pard\nowidctlpar Very good post and real life example, Chris. Indeed, math is used in all business and it's very important to get all numbers right. Sometimes it's relatively easy, for example when you're doing reporting. You just need to be very careful with data collection and calculation. But when we try to predict a future number, things can become very challenging.  Yesterday I read  an article on Yahoo news about federal deficit. I can't remember the exact details. But basically in 2000 the experts in the government predicted that we would have a big federal surplus  in the decade of 2001-2010 which is laughingly off target when we looked at it now. \par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-720\li720\par

\pard\nowidctlpar It's a good method, Rhonda. It is true that something that you feel very natural and easy may be a hard problem for some other people and vice versa. Although challenging, it is often very beneficial (and fun I might add) to learn something that you're not good at. The point is repeating. If you're not comfortable with a rule or technique, you just need to practice with it lots of times. Pretty soon it will get imprinted into your mind.  Of course, you have to practice consciously as what you're doing with the order of operations.\par
Don't rush through solving a problem instead taking your time to make sure every step is correct. \par
\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-720\li720\par

\pard\nowidctlpar   Some post has made a good analogy between the order of operation and putting on socks first then shoes. But regarding your thoughtful post, I would like to point out some difference.  It's impossible to put on shoes before socks, at least for normal people. But the math order of operations is not exactly like that. When math was in its infancy, people might follow different order to calculate the same expression. But this was just chaos and made it very hard to communicate mathematically.  So mathematicians decided to use a common acceptable order so everyone would be on the same page. So came the PEMDAS.  But this by no means to say that PEMDAS is better than PEASMD.  Should they have chosen the latter order, everything would still have worked out fine. It is just now that PEMDAS is the thousand-year standard tradition so everyone uses it. \par
\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-720\li720\par

\pard\nowidctlpar Great discussion connecting order of operations to our every day life. I think putting together boxed furniture is also a good example of following order of operation. It amazes me to see a  furniture being built from pieces. Though it is a step by step process, it helps to read the whole instruction first to have the whole picture in mind. \par
Not only in math, many other subject areas requires following the order of operations. Like in chemistry, different compounds need to put in certain order to ensure proper reaction. One student in my previous class talked about the order of operations in the operating room to ensure that surgeon works on the correct body part. \par
\fs24\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-720\li720\par

\pard\nowidctlpar\fs20 Alician, you stated that " Possible outcomes of ignoring it is totally wrong answers, partially wrong answers , or correct answers but the wong sign(- or +). " You are absolutely correct. Here are some examples where the order of operation is ignored. \par
\par
Example #1:  3+5*2. The correct answer is 13. But if you don't follow the order of operation, you may get the answer 16 by first adding 3 and 5 and then multiplying 2. \par
\par
Example #2: (3+5)*2. The correct answer is 16. But if you don't follow the order of operation, you may get the answer 13 by ignoring the parenthesis. \par
\par
