\pard\nowidctlpar Nowadays everyone in China reads from left to right, be it novel or math expression. But I heard that long time ago in old China, people read books column by column (not row by row) and from right to left, kind of weird isn't it?  The catch is that in theory  any order works  as long as it can only result in one unique answer. For example, there is nothing wrong with the order PEASMD by which we would have 2+3*2=5*2=10. Because PEMDAS was selected as the official order of operation when math was in its infancy, it became the only correct order. \par
